{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric aggregate step we obtained a ranked list of component-KPI pairs with points above their global P95 inside the incident window. Top candidates include many Redis01 KPIs, Tomcat03 request/thread KPIs, apache01 CPU, Redis02 and Mysql01 CPU-related KPIs. Each candidate currently shows only a small number of anomalous points in the window (anomalies_in_window_count mostly = 2) but we must treat faults as consecutive anomalous sub-series (not isolated spikes). Next we need to perform fault identification: find consecutive-minute anomaly segments (value > global_P95) within the incident window for those candidate component-KPI series, measure their start/end timestamps, duration, peak value, and severity relative to the global P95 (severity_pct = (max_value - global_P95) / global_P95 * 100). This will help filter out isolated spikes and surface faults with significant deviation (>>50%) which are more likely true root causes. After that we can use traces/logs to further localize if multiple service-level faults remain.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric.csv and the previously stored aggregate table (result_df), select all component-KPI rows where anomalies_in_window_count > 0. For each selected (cmdb_id, kpi_name) do the following in code: 1) Load full metric time series for that cmdb_id and kpi_name from metric.csv (use full series to keep global_P95 consistent with earlier results); 2) Filter the series to the incident window 2021-03-10 16:30:00 to 2021-03-10 17:00:00 (UTC+8); 3) Mark points where value > global_P95 (use the global_P95 from result_df for that pair); 4) Group marked points into consecutive-minute segments (consecutive timestamps with no gaps); 5) For each segment produce one row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, fault_start_ts_local, fault_end_ts_local, duration_minutes (inclusive minutes), max_value_in_segment, severity_pct = (max_value_in_segment - global_P95)/global_P95*100; 6) Also produce per-cmdb_id counts of segments and per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) total segments. Return two compact tables: A) the fault segments table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severity_pct descending; B) a summary table of top 10 cmdb_id by number_of_segments (columns: cmdb_id, number_of_segments). Keep outputs concise and do not print full raw series." }

